node.text: "Wayfinding" systems are the smart design tools that help people navigate from place to place. It's a universal language that exists everywhere — from the roads we drive, the paths we walk, and the airports and malls we traverse. There's also a natural version in our brains. Without it, we'd be getting lost a whole lot more.

node.title: The Subtle Design Keeping Us From Getting Lost

node.text:
The 9/11 terror attack on New York killed 2,753 people and in the two decades since, the scale of the losses for the city and Wall Street still stagger. Three out of every four people who worked in New York for the brokerage Cantor Fitzgerald, 658 in all, died when the North Tower collapsed. 

At the boutique bank Keefe, Bruyette & Woods, 67 of the 171 New York employees were killed when the South Tower fell. At Aon, 176 were killed.

The list goes on. 

On this 20th anniversary, Wall Street looks back.

node.text:
"I would describe cryptocurrencies as a limited supply of nothing."

John Paulson—who's famous bet against subprime housing made him and investors $20 billion—says crypto is a "worthless" bubble and he calls SPACs, one of the hottest investing tools, a losing proposition.

Paulson told @bloombergtv in an interview on "Bloomberg Wealth with David Rubenstein" he's more concerned about rising prices. The rapidly expanding money supply could push inflation rates well above current expectations, he said, and gold, which he’s backed for years, is primed for its moment.

Paulson’s dismissal of crypto is sure to attract critics after digital assets vastly outperformed gold in recent years. Watch the full episode Tuesday at 9pm ET on BloombergTV and read the Big Take in our stories.

node.title: Cryptocurrencies are a Bubble, Says Billionaire Paulson

node.text:
China's growing ranks of rural entrepreneurs are getting rich peddling their produce on social media. 

One of the scene's stars is Jin Guowei, aka Brother Pomegranate — an internet sensation with 7.3 million followers and 300 million yuan ($46 million) of sales in 2020. (video via @quicktake)

node.title: Livestreaming Farmers Earn Millions From Fruit on China’s TikTok

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Bloomberg Business on September 16, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'PAPIERS DÉCOUPÉS 水 MATISSE New York renters are finding the era pandemic discounts well and truly over be Wat'.

node.text:
New York landlords are jacking up rents — often by 50, 60 or 70% — on tenants who locked in deals last year when prices were in freefall.

For ten months, the pandemic-hit rental market in Manhattan has given people the chance of a lifetime to move into the apartment of their dreams. Now steep hikes mean some renters are being forced to move at a time when the market is roaring back to nearly pre-pandemic levels.

Tenants, like 24-year-old Claire Smith, have limited options. Though she knows she has to find a new place, she's pinning her hopes on a cooling of the market some predict will happen in the fall. Tap the link in our bio to read in full.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Bloomberg Business on September 16, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'B! UXP urban-Air Poru Flying-taxi taxi hubs are planned for 65 cities, spanning London toLA Bloomberg'.

node.text:
A venture involving Hyundai wants to bring flying taxis to a city near you.
 
The South Korean automaker has announced plans to build a network of 65 hubs for vertical take-off and landing craft in a tie-up with infrastructure firm Urban-Air Port.

A first site in Coventry, England, is due to open in early 2022, with more bases in the U.K., U.S., France, Germany, Australia and Asia in the pipeline. Tap the link in our bio to see more. 

📷: Urban-Air Port rendering

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Bloomberg Business on September 16, 2021. May be an image of one or more people, people standing and text that says 'Franceis furious with Biden for cutting itout of his submarinedea Bloomberg'.

node.text:
France's top diplomat unleashed a stream of invective against President Joe Biden after the U.S. and the U.K. announced a new security alliance which will cost the French defense industry some A$90 billion (56 billion euros).
 
Officials in Paris were blindsided on Wednesday night when the U.S. and the U.K. announced a new partnership to supply Australia with nuclear-powered submarines. 

Foreign Minister Jean-Yves Le Drian said he felt "stabbed in the back" over the "unacceptable" deal that would hurt French business and shut the country's military out of a key initiative to build a bulwark against China. Tap the link in our bio for more.

📷: Win McNamee / Getty Images

"Thank you Boris, and I want to thank that fella Down Under."

Australian Prime Minister Scott Morrison trended on social media after U.S. President Joe Biden appeared to forget his name during a press conference on a new security partnership.

#ThatFellaDownUnder then ensued, becoming the top trending hashtag on Australian Twitter. Tap the link in our bio for more.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Bloomberg Business in San Salvador. May be an image of text that says 'ti-government protesters burn Bitcoin ATMinEl BUKELS Salvador EROTE Bloomberg'.

node.text:
Anti-government marchers took to the streets in El Salvador to protest the adoption of Bitcoin as legal tender and recent moves by President Nayib Bukele to consolidate power.
 
Several thousand people marched to the central plaza in the country’s capital of San Salvador, carrying signs declaring "no to dictatorship" and "we were defrauded by Bitcoin." A Bitcoin ATM kiosk installed last month was set alight.

"Bitcoin was a very big economic decision, and it was done totally illogically, sent to congress and passed the same day," opposition lawmaker Claudia Ortiz said in an interview, adding it was unclear who was behind the vandalism. Full story at the link in our bio.

Four civilians with no astronaut training blasted off on a three-day orbital flight on a SpaceX rocket, a launch some see as the start of a new era of human space travel.

On board were a tech billionaire, a childhood-cancer survivor, a geoscience professor and an Air Force veteran. Tap the link in our bio for more.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Bloomberg Business on September 15, 2021. May be an image of 3 people and text that says 'Nicki Minaj' tweets impotence prompt White House to offer vaccine answers Bloomberg'.

node.text:
The White House offered to connect Nicki Minaj with one of the Biden administration’s doctors to address her questions about the Covid-19 vaccine, after her viral and erroneous tweet claiming the shot causes impotence.

Officials said they had offered similar calls to others concerned about the vaccine, part of an aggressive public relations campaign to beat back rampant disinformation about the vaccine’s safety and effectiveness.

Dr. Anthony Fauci, the leading U.S. infectious disease expert, had already dismissed the rapper’s claim about her cousin’s friend in Trinidad as misinformation. Link in bio for more.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Bloomberg Business on September 15, 2021. May be an image of monument and text.

node.text:
The latest plan released by House Democrats scales back many of President Biden’s proposals to hike taxes on corporations and rich investors, as moderates and progressives tussle over how far to go to address inequality. But they included an element the White House left out.

The proposal cracks down on a number of strategies that have made the estate-and-gift tax easy to avoid if you hire the right advisers. That could upend how the top 0.1% manages their fortunes and whether they can move millions, sometimes billions, of dollars’ worth of assets outside their estates tax-free.

Significantly, it takes aim at sales or gifts to popular vehicles known as “intentionally defective grantor trusts.” Find out more at the link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Bloomberg Business on September 15, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Cryptokidfraudster kid fraudster getsseven and a half years for Ponzi Ponzischeme Tether Bloomberg'.

node.text:
Stefan Qin’s investors thought they’d found a sure thing — a hedge fund that was generating 500% returns by exploiting the price gaps between cryptocurrencies on 40 exchanges throughout the world. The Wall Street Journal wrote a profile of him in 2018, when he managed $23.5 million. By 2020, he’d raised more than $90 million.

Instead, the 24-year-old self-proclaimed math whiz used investors’ money on a lavish lifestyle, including a $23,000-a-month Manhattan penthouse apartment, and failed investments in initial coin offerings and real estate. Federal prosecutors said Qin defrauded more than 100 people.

More than a dozen of them wrote letters to U.S. District Judge Valerie Caproni, who sentenced him Wednesday to seven and a half years and called him “a potentially very dangerous person.” Several said they had lost their life savings to Qin. Read more at the link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Bloomberg Business on September 15, 2021. May be an image of 2 people and text that says 'NIKES Food costs are rising. Politicians will pay the price. Bloomberg'.

node.text:
Whether for bread, rice or tortillas, governments across the world know that rising food costs can come with a political price. The dilemma is whether they can do enough to prevent having to pay it.

Global food prices were up 33% in August from a year earlier with vegetable oil, grains and meat on the rise. And it’s not likely to get better as extreme weather, soaring freight and fertilizer costs, shipping bottlenecks and labor shortages compound the problem.

From Europe to Turkey and India, politicians are now handing out more aid, ordering sellers to cut prices and tinkering with trade rules to mitigate the impact on consumers. Tap the link in our bio to read more.

node.text:
The Bloomberg @businessweek B-School ranking is out and Stanford is the top MBA program once again. IMD and CEIBS also retained their No. 1 spots in Europe and Asia-Pacific, respectively.

For the first time, the list also includes a Diversity Index measuring U.S. schools on race, ethnicity, and gender in their classes. See the full ranking at the link in bio. (via @businessweek + @bloombergequality)

node.text:
A SpaceX rocket is set to launch four civilians into orbit for a three-day voyage circling the Earth, possibly as soon as this evening.
 
No professional astronauts will be on board, with the so-called Inspiration4 crew relying on the capsule's autonomous capabilities for navigation, life support and safe return.
 
The passengers includes tech billionaire Jared Isaacman, who reportedly paid $200 million to be on the trip — in addition to a $100 million donation pledge. Tap the link in bio for who else is going, and why SpaceX is sending them up.
